[recv] {"type": "turn_end", "message": {"role": "assistant", "content": [{"type": "thinking", "thinking": "**Analyzing native image issues**\n\nI think we need to respond without making code changes, but the user might expect a fix. I could inspect the status to check for forbidden metadata since an empty directory won't be tracked, but it could matter externally. \n\nIt seems the test passed in the JVM, but there's a failure in native-image before analysis. Perhaps there's a way to configure temp options via the NATIVE_IMAGE_OPTIONS environment variable since the native image uses a hardcoded temp directory. I’ll need to determine if there's a workaround.\n\n**Examining native image configuration**\n\nI'm realizing that in the native image runtime, SystemPropertiesSupport returns /tmp lazily, but I wonder if system properties can be set via the command line. The native executable does support -D, but it seems that it might be more of a builder argument than a Java property of the driver. It looks like TMPDIR is ignored when using Files.createTempDirectory.\n\nI might consider setting _JAVA_OPTIONS, but since the native executable isn't the same as the JVM, that may not apply. The user didn't ask for a solution but just reported a failure. It might be useful to clarify that tests pass in the JVM, but the native failure is likely due to the full temp file system.\n\n**Considering build output cleanup**\n\nI’m thinking it might be a good idea to clean generated build outputs to free up space since we shouldn't run tests right now. The failure seems related to an external workflow, likely due to insufficient space while trying to create a tiny temp directory in /tmp.\n\nIt seems that no test patch can fix this unless we remove empty metadata. It's worth investigating if Native Image 25 has an environment option to set the driver temp directory. We could also consider reducing native build space.", "thinkingSignature": "{\"id\":\"rs_02de86cb43a73b800169fe35f6f4e08195b41